        <headline>Special Weather Statement issued March 31 at 1:48AM EDT by NWS Charleston WV</headline>
        <description>At 147 AM EDT, Doppler radar was tracking strong thunderstorms along
a line extending from near Buffalo to Ulysses. Movement was east at
45 mph.

HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 50 mph and pea size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor hail damage to vegetation is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
Ranger, Louisa, Barboursville, Nitro, Salt Rock, Palermo, Pea Ridge,
Genoa, Poca, Fraziers Bottom, Harts, Buffalo, Cross Lanes, Gill,
Gallup, Sweetland, Harmony, West Hamlin, Clifford, and Ulysses.

This includes the following highways...
Interstate 77 in West Virginia between mile markers 109 and 127.
Interstate 64 in West Virginia between mile markers 17 and 53.
Route 119 between mile markers 66 and 67.
</description>
        <instruction>If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with these storms and may lead
to localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with these storms.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.

A Severe Thunderstorm Watch remains in effect until 600 AM EDT for
northeastern Kentucky...and central, southern, western and
northwestern West Virginia.</instruction>
